# Home Box - Thin-Client Runbook

> The Linux laptop is the sole PAI host. The Mac and phone are thin clients that reach it
> over Tailscale and drive `claude` remotely. No file sync, one source of truth.
> Remote access is `rc` (remote claude), not Telegram. Telegram is demoted to outbound notifications only.
>
> Status: PLAN. Nothing here is built yet - this is the build sheet for when the laptop arrives.
> Grounded in the live launchd plists, the cadence runner, and a macOS-ism scan of `~/.claude` (2026-06-03).

---

## The model

```
   Linux laptop ("box")                      Mac / iPhone (thin clients)
   ────────────────────                      ───────────────────────────
   ~/.claude  (the ONLY PAI)                 nothing local to keep in sync
   Pulse :31337  (systemd)        ◄── Tailscale ──►   rc  → mosh + tmux → claude
   cadence timers (systemd)                  VS Code Remote-SSH (heavy work)
   claude CLI + agents                       browser → http://box:31337 (Pulse)
   rclone OneDrive mount
```

Single source of truth on the box. The Mac stops being a PAI host and becomes a terminal onto one. The cost of this is a single point of failure (covered in Backup / DR) - accepted deliberately in exchange for never reconciling two divergent `~/.claude` trees again.

**Naming.** Below I assume the Linux user is `nick`, home is `/home/nick`, and the Tailscale MagicDNS name is `box`. Adjust if different. Everything uses `$HOME` / `%h` so the literal path rarely matters.

---

## What "claude rc" is

`rc` is a one-word command on the Mac and phone that drops you straight into a live `claude` on the box:

- It `mosh`es to the box over Tailscale (mosh, not plain ssh, because it survives laptop sleep, wifi changes, and tethering - the exact things that made the Telegram round-trip feel flaky).
- It attaches a **persistent `tmux` session** named `pai`, creating it if absent. The session lives on the box, so closing the lid on the Mac or locking the phone does not kill the work. Reconnect and you are exactly where you left off.
- Inside that session you run `claude` against `~/.claude`. Same CLI you use now, just hosted remotely.

That is the whole trick: the agent runs on the always-on box; `rc` is just a durable window onto it. It replaces Telegram as the primary interface. (VS Code Remote-SSH and the Pulse web UI are the other two windows; Telegram stays only for push digests.)

If you meant something more specific by "claude rc" (e.g. Claude Code's own web/mobile remote), tell me and I will swap the access layer - the rest of the runbook (host, services, DR) is unchanged.

